Reference-contexts: Because uncertainty is such an important aspect of this problem, we have undertaken a comparative study of several methods for representing and reasoning with uncertainty in this domain. The methods under consideration are certainty factors (Buchanan and Shortliffe 1984), Bayesian networks <ref> (Pearl 1988) </ref>, Dempster-Shafer theory (Shafer 1976), and fuzzy logic (Zadeh 1965). This report presents a description of our preliminary results using Dempster-Shafer theory for waste characterization. In particular, we have designed and implemented a small Dempster-Shafer system that addresses the first two decision points in Figure 1. <p> The major appeal of the theory is that it admits partially specified models and it is compatible with classical proof-based style of logical inference, sharing the syntax of deductive databases and logic programming <ref> (Pearl 1988) </ref>. The two major concepts of Dempster-Shafer (D-S) theory are the frame of discernment and the basic probability assignment (Stefik 1995). In D-S theory, the domain must be described using an exhaustive, mutually exclusive set of ground elements.
